def L(lv,t,c,code='',tip=''):return(lv,t,c,code,tip)
SQL=[
L(1,'What is SQL?','SQL (Structured Query Language) is the standard language for interacting with relational databases. It lets you create, read, update, and delete data stored in tables. SQL commands are not case-sensitive, but writing keywords in UPPERCASE is a common convention for readability.','SELECT * FROM users;\n\n-- This gets all rows and columns\n-- from the users table\n\n-- Comments start with --','SQL is used by almost every application that stores data: social media, banking, e-commerce, healthcare, and more. It is one of the most valuable skills in tech.'),
L(1,'Tables and Rows','A database organizes data in tables. Each table has columns (fields/attributes) and rows (records). Think of it like a spreadsheet. Every table should have a primary key column (usually id) that uniquely identifies each row.','-- A "users" table:\n-- | id | name    | email          | age |\n-- |----|---------|----------------|-----|\n-- | 1  | Alice   | alice@mail.com | 25  |\n-- | 2  | Bob     | bob@mail.com   | 30  |','The primary key (usually id) must be unique for every row. It is how the database identifies and references specific records.'),
L(2,'SELECT Basics','SELECT retrieves data from tables — it is the most common SQL command. Use * to get all columns, or list specific column names separated by commas. Use AS to rename columns in the output (aliases).','-- Get all columns\nSELECT * FROM products;\n\n-- Get specific columns only\nSELECT name, price FROM products;\n\n-- With aliases\nSELECT name AS product_name,\n       price AS cost\nFROM products;','Always select only the columns you need instead of using *. It is faster, uses less memory, and makes your intent clear.'),
L(2,'DISTINCT and LIMIT','DISTINCT removes duplicate values from results. LIMIT restricts how many rows are returned — essential for pagination. Use OFFSET to skip rows: page 1 uses OFFSET 0, page 2 uses OFFSET 10, etc.','-- Unique categories only\nSELECT DISTINCT category\nFROM products;\n\n-- First 10 results\nSELECT * FROM users\nLIMIT 10;\n\n-- Pagination: skip 20, get next 10\nSELECT * FROM users\nLIMIT 10 OFFSET 20;','DISTINCT applies to the entire row. SELECT DISTINCT city, country returns unique city-country combinations, not just unique cities.'),
L(3,'WHERE — Filtering Rows','WHERE filters which rows are returned based on conditions. Only rows matching the condition appear in results. Use AND to require both conditions, OR for either, and LIKE for pattern matching.','SELECT * FROM users\nWHERE age >= 18;\n\nSELECT * FROM products\nWHERE price < 50\n  AND category = \'Electronics\';\n\nSELECT * FROM users\nWHERE name LIKE \'A%\';','LIKE uses % for any characters and _ for exactly one character. \'A%\' matches Alice, Adam, Angela. \'_ob\' matches Bob, Rob.'),
L(3,'IN, BETWEEN, and NULL','IN checks if a value matches any item in a list. BETWEEN checks if a value falls within a range (inclusive). For NULL (missing/unknown values), always use IS NULL or IS NOT NULL — never use = NULL.','SELECT * FROM users\nWHERE country IN (\'US\', \'UK\', \'CA\');\n\nSELECT * FROM products\nWHERE price BETWEEN 10 AND 50;\n\nSELECT * FROM users\nWHERE email IS NOT NULL;','NULL means "unknown" — it is not zero, not empty, not false. You CANNOT use = NULL or != NULL. Always use IS NULL or IS NOT NULL.'),
L(4,'ORDER BY — Sorting Results','ORDER BY sorts the output by one or more columns. ASC (ascending) is the default — smallest to largest. DESC (descending) goes largest to smallest. You can sort by multiple columns with priority.','SELECT * FROM products\nORDER BY price DESC;\n\n-- Multi-column sort\nSELECT * FROM users\nORDER BY country ASC, name ASC;\n\n-- Sort by column position\nSELECT name, age FROM users\nORDER BY 2 DESC;  -- sort by age','ORDER BY runs AFTER WHERE. First filter the rows you want, then sort the results. Without ORDER BY, row order is not guaranteed.'),
L(4,'CASE Expressions','CASE works like if/else inside a SQL query. It creates computed columns based on conditions. CASE can be used in SELECT, WHERE, ORDER BY, and even inside aggregate functions.','SELECT name, price,\n  CASE\n    WHEN price > 100 THEN \'Expensive\'\n    WHEN price > 50  THEN \'Medium\'\n    ELSE \'Budget\'\n  END AS price_tier\nFROM products\nORDER BY price DESC;','Every CASE must end with END. The ELSE clause is optional but recommended — without it, unmatched rows get NULL.'),
L(5,'Aggregate Functions','Aggregate functions calculate a single value from multiple rows: COUNT (how many), SUM (total), AVG (average), MIN (smallest), MAX (largest). They collapse many rows into one result.','SELECT COUNT(*) AS total_users\nFROM users;\n\nSELECT\n  AVG(price) AS avg_price,\n  MAX(price) AS highest,\n  MIN(price) AS lowest,\n  SUM(price) AS total_value\nFROM products;','COUNT(*) counts ALL rows including nulls. COUNT(column) only counts rows where that column is NOT null. This distinction matters.'),
L(5,'Aggregates with WHERE','Filter rows first with WHERE, then apply aggregate functions to the filtered results. The execution order is: FROM → WHERE → aggregation. You cannot use aggregate functions inside WHERE.','SELECT COUNT(*) AS adult_count\nFROM users\nWHERE age >= 18;\n\nSELECT\n  AVG(price) AS avg_price\nFROM products\nWHERE category = \'Electronics\';','You CANNOT write WHERE AVG(price) > 50 — aggregates are not allowed in WHERE. Use HAVING (next lesson) for filtering on aggregate results.'),
L(6,'GROUP BY','GROUP BY splits rows into groups and applies aggregate functions to each group separately. Every non-aggregate column in SELECT must also appear in GROUP BY — this is a strict rule.','SELECT category,\n       COUNT(*) AS product_count,\n       AVG(price) AS avg_price\nFROM products\nGROUP BY category;','Every column in SELECT must either be in GROUP BY or wrapped in an aggregate function (COUNT, SUM, AVG, etc.). Violating this rule causes errors.'),
L(6,'HAVING — Filter Groups','HAVING filters groups AFTER aggregation — it is the equivalent of WHERE but for aggregate results. Use WHERE to filter individual rows before grouping, and HAVING to filter groups after.','SELECT category, COUNT(*) AS total\nFROM products\nGROUP BY category\nHAVING COUNT(*) > 10;\n\n-- WHERE = before grouping\n-- HAVING = after grouping\nSELECT category, AVG(price) AS avg\nFROM products\nWHERE price > 0\nGROUP BY category\nHAVING AVG(price) > 50;','Execution order: FROM → WHERE → GROUP BY → HAVING → SELECT → ORDER BY. WHERE filters rows, HAVING filters groups.'),
L(7,'INNER JOIN','JOIN combines rows from two or more tables based on a related column (usually a foreign key). INNER JOIN returns only rows that have matches in BOTH tables — unmatched rows are excluded.','SELECT orders.id, users.name, orders.total\nFROM orders\nINNER JOIN users\n  ON orders.user_id = users.id;\n\n-- With shorter aliases\nSELECT o.id, u.name, o.total\nFROM orders o\nJOIN users u ON o.user_id = u.id;','INNER JOIN and JOIN mean exactly the same thing — the INNER keyword is optional. Most developers just write JOIN.'),
L(7,'LEFT and RIGHT JOIN','LEFT JOIN returns ALL rows from the left table, and matching rows from the right table. If there is no match, the right side columns are NULL. RIGHT JOIN does the opposite.','-- All users, even those with no orders\nSELECT u.name,\n       COUNT(o.id) AS order_count\nFROM users u\nLEFT JOIN orders o\n  ON u.id = o.user_id\nGROUP BY u.name;','LEFT JOIN is much more common than RIGHT JOIN. You can always convert a RIGHT JOIN to a LEFT JOIN by swapping the table order.'),
L(8,'Multiple Joins','Join three or more tables by chaining JOIN clauses. Each JOIN connects two tables through a shared column. Read multi-table queries left to right: start with the main table and join related ones.','SELECT o.id AS order_id,\n       u.name AS customer,\n       p.name AS product,\n       oi.quantity\nFROM orders o\nJOIN users u ON o.user_id = u.id\nJOIN order_items oi ON o.id = oi.order_id\nJOIN products p ON oi.product_id = p.id;','Each JOIN adds one table. Three JOINs connect four tables. The ON clause specifies which columns link the tables together.'),
L(8,'Self Join','A table can be joined with itself to compare rows within the same table. This is useful for hierarchical data like employees and managers, or finding related records in the same table.','SELECT e.name AS employee,\n       m.name AS manager\nFROM employees e\nLEFT JOIN employees m\n  ON e.manager_id = m.id;','Use different aliases (e for employee, m for manager) to distinguish the two copies of the same table in your query.'),
L(9,'Subqueries','A subquery is a query nested inside another query. It can appear in WHERE, FROM, or SELECT clauses. Use subqueries to break complex questions into smaller, manageable steps.','-- Find users who placed orders\nSELECT name FROM users\nWHERE id IN (\n  SELECT DISTINCT user_id FROM orders\n);\n\n-- Products above average price\nSELECT name, price FROM products\nWHERE price > (\n  SELECT AVG(price) FROM products\n);','A subquery in WHERE with a single value uses = or >. With multiple values, use IN. The inner query runs first, then the outer query uses its result.'),
L(9,'EXISTS','EXISTS checks whether a subquery returns any rows at all (true/false). It is often faster than IN for large datasets because it stops searching as soon as it finds one match.','-- Users who have at least one order\nSELECT name FROM users u\nWHERE EXISTS (\n  SELECT 1 FROM orders o\n  WHERE o.user_id = u.id\n);\n\n-- Users with NO orders\nSELECT name FROM users u\nWHERE NOT EXISTS (\n  SELECT 1 FROM orders o\n  WHERE o.user_id = u.id\n);','EXISTS returns true/false. SELECT 1 is conventional — the actual value does not matter since EXISTS only checks if ANY row is returned.'),
L(10,'INSERT — Adding Data','INSERT adds new rows to a table. Always list column names explicitly — this protects your code if columns are added or reordered later. You can insert one row or multiple rows at once.','INSERT INTO users (name, email, age)\nVALUES (\'Alice\', \'a@mail.com\', 25);\n\n-- Multiple rows at once\nINSERT INTO users (name, email, age)\nVALUES\n  (\'Bob\', \'b@mail.com\', 30),\n  (\'Charlie\', \'c@mail.com\', 28);','Always list column names in INSERT: INSERT INTO users (name, email) VALUES (...). Never rely on column order — it can change.'),
L(10,'UPDATE and DELETE','UPDATE modifies existing rows. DELETE removes rows entirely. ALWAYS use WHERE with both — without it, you affect EVERY row in the table. Test your WHERE clause with SELECT first.','UPDATE users\nSET age = 26, email = \'new@mail.com\'\nWHERE id = 1;\n\nDELETE FROM orders\nWHERE created_at < \'2023-01-01\';\n\n-- DANGER: without WHERE\n-- DELETE FROM users;  -- deletes ALL rows!','Always run SELECT with your WHERE clause first to verify which rows will be affected before running UPDATE or DELETE. This prevents catastrophic data loss.'),
L(11,'CREATE TABLE','CREATE TABLE defines a new table with column names, data types, and constraints. Common types: INTEGER, VARCHAR(n), TEXT, DECIMAL(p,s), BOOLEAN, DATE, TIMESTAMP.','CREATE TABLE products (\n  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n  name VARCHAR(200) NOT NULL,\n  price DECIMAL(10, 2) DEFAULT 0.00,\n  category VARCHAR(100),\n  created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW()\n);','PRIMARY KEY uniquely identifies each row. SERIAL auto-increments the id. NOT NULL means the column must always have a value.'),
L(11,'ALTER and DROP TABLE','ALTER TABLE modifies an existing table\'s structure: add columns, remove columns, rename columns, or change data types. DROP TABLE permanently deletes the entire table and all its data.','ALTER TABLE users\nADD COLUMN phone VARCHAR(20);\n\nALTER TABLE users\nDROP COLUMN phone;\n\nALTER TABLE products\nRENAME COLUMN cost TO price;\n\n-- Permanent deletion!\nDROP TABLE IF EXISTS temp_data;','Use IF EXISTS with DROP to avoid errors when the table might not exist. Always back up data before dropping tables — there is no undo.'),
L(12,'NOT NULL and DEFAULT','NOT NULL ensures a column always has a value — INSERT without it fails. DEFAULT provides an automatic value when none is specified during INSERT. Combine both for required fields with sensible fallbacks.','CREATE TABLE tasks (\n  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n  title VARCHAR(200) NOT NULL,\n  status VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT \'pending\',\n  priority INT DEFAULT 0,\n  created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW()\n);','NOT NULL + DEFAULT work together: the column always has a value. NOT NULL alone means the insert MUST provide a value. DEFAULT alone allows explicit NULLs.'),
L(12,'UNIQUE and CHECK Constraints','UNIQUE prevents duplicate values in a column — no two rows can have the same value. CHECK enforces a rule that values must satisfy. Both protect data integrity at the database level.','CREATE TABLE users (\n  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n  email VARCHAR(255) UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n  age INT CHECK (age >= 0 AND age < 150),\n  role VARCHAR(20) CHECK (\n    role IN (\'admin\', \'user\', \'guest\')\n  )\n);','UNIQUE allows multiple NULL values by default. Combine UNIQUE NOT NULL when you want exactly one non-null value per row.'),
L(13,'Indexes','Indexes speed up searches by creating a lookup structure — like a book\'s index. They trade storage space for dramatically faster query performance. Add indexes on columns you frequently filter, search, or join on.','-- Create an index\nCREATE INDEX idx_users_email\nON users(email);\n\n-- Composite index (multiple columns)\nCREATE INDEX idx_orders_user_date\nON orders(user_id, created_at);\n\n-- Check if index is used\nEXPLAIN SELECT * FROM users\nWHERE email = \'alice@mail.com\';','Every index speeds up reads but slows down writes (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE). Only index columns that are frequently searched or filtered.'),
L(13,'Index Types and Strategy','B-tree (default) handles equality and range queries. Partial indexes only index a subset of rows. Unique indexes enforce uniqueness while also speeding up lookups.','-- Default B-tree (range queries)\nCREATE INDEX idx_price\nON products(price);\n\n-- Partial index (only active users)\nCREATE INDEX idx_active_users\nON users(email)\nWHERE is_active = true;\n\n-- Unique index\nCREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx_unique_email\nON users(email);','Partial indexes are smaller and faster because they only include rows matching a condition. Use them when you frequently query a specific subset of data.'),
L(14,'Transactions','Transactions group multiple operations into one atomic unit: either ALL succeed (COMMIT) or ALL fail (ROLLBACK). This prevents partial updates that would leave your data in an inconsistent state.','BEGIN;\n\nUPDATE accounts\nSET balance = balance - 100\nWHERE id = 1;\n\nUPDATE accounts\nSET balance = balance + 100\nWHERE id = 2;\n\n-- If everything worked:\nCOMMIT;\n-- If something failed:\n-- ROLLBACK;','Transactions are essential for financial operations. In a bank transfer, you never want money deducted from one account without being added to another.'),
L(14,'ACID Properties','Databases follow ACID principles: Atomicity (all or nothing), Consistency (data stays valid), Isolation (transactions don\'t interfere with each other), Durability (committed data survives crashes).','-- Atomicity: both succeed or both fail\nBEGIN;\n  INSERT INTO orders (...) VALUES (...);\n  UPDATE inventory SET qty = qty - 1\n    WHERE product_id = 1;\nCOMMIT;\n\n-- If UPDATE fails,\n-- the INSERT is also rolled back','Isolation levels control how concurrent transactions interact. Read Committed is the default in PostgreSQL and works for most applications.'),
L(15,'Window Functions','Window functions perform calculations across related rows WITHOUT collapsing them into groups (unlike GROUP BY). Each row keeps its identity while gaining access to aggregate data from its group.','SELECT name, department, salary,\n  RANK() OVER (\n    PARTITION BY department\n    ORDER BY salary DESC\n  ) AS dept_rank,\n  AVG(salary) OVER (\n    PARTITION BY department\n  ) AS dept_avg\nFROM employees;','PARTITION BY divides rows into groups (like GROUP BY). ORDER BY within OVER() determines the calculation order. RANK(), ROW_NUMBER(), and LAG() are common window functions.'),
L(15,'CTEs — Common Table Expressions','CTEs (WITH clause) create named temporary result sets that exist only for one query. They make complex queries readable by breaking them into named, logical steps.','WITH top_customers AS (\n  SELECT user_id,\n         SUM(total) AS total_spent\n  FROM orders\n  GROUP BY user_id\n  HAVING SUM(total) > 1000\n)\nSELECT u.name, tc.total_spent\nFROM top_customers tc\nJOIN users u ON tc.user_id = u.id\nORDER BY tc.total_spent DESC;','CTEs are like temporary views scoped to a single query. They make complex queries much easier to read, debug, and maintain.'),
]
